05909nam a22009615i 9780520917613DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20201998cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209176137 a10.1525/97805209176132doi  a(DE-B1597)570183  a(OCoLC)1224278355  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aK355b.H333 1998 7aPHI0190002bisacsh00aHabermas on Law and Democracy :bCritical Exchanges /ced. by Michel Rosenfeld, Andrew Arato.  aReprint 2020 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2020] 4c©1998  a1 online resource (486 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPhilosophy, Social Theory, and the Rule of Law ;v60 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the first essay, Habermas himself succinctly presents the centerpiece of his theory: his proceduralist paradigm of law. The following essays comprise elaborations, criticisms, and further explorations by others of the most salient issues addressed in his theory. The distinguished group of contributors—internationally prominent scholars in the fields of law, philosophy, and social theory—includes many who have been closely identified with Habermas as well as some of his best-known critics. The final essay is a thorough and lengthy reply by Habermas, which not only engages the most important arguments raised in the preceding essays but also further elaborates and refines some of his own key contributions in Between Facts and Norms. This volume will be essential reading for philosophers, legal scholars, and political and social theorists concerned with understanding the work of one of the leading philosophers of our age. These provocative, in-depth debates between Jürgen Habermas and a wide range of his critics relate to the philosopher's contribution to legal and democratic theory in his recently published Between Facts and Norms. Drawing upon his discourse theory, Habermas has elaborated a novel and powerful account of law that purports to bridge the gap between democracy and rights, by conceiving law to be at once self-imposed and binding.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aDemocracyvCongresses. 0aDemocracy. 0aDroitxPhilosophie. 0aDémocratie. 0aLawxPhilosophyvCongresses. 0aLawxPhilosophy. 0aSociological jurisprudencevCongresses. 0aSociological jurisprudence. 0aSociologie juridique. 4aHabermas. 4aJürgen Habermas. 4aOthers. 4ademocracy. 4ademocratic theory. 4aethics. 4alaw. 4amoral philosophy. 4aphilosophy. 4apolitical philosophy. 4asocial philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh1 aAlexy, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArato, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArato, Andrew, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBernstein, Richard J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForbath, William E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGünther, Klaus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHabermas, Jürgen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacobson, Arthur J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLenoble, Jacques, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLuhmann, Niklas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCarthy, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMichelman, Frank I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPower, Michael K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPreuss, Ulrich K., econtributor.4ctb4https://i